      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Survival of the Fakest,'' by Frank Rich (column, Aug. 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Survival of the Fakest,'' by Frank Rich (column, Aug. 26):</p>
        <p>Mr. Rich's ''plague on both their houses'' column about the money-grubbing antics of both Democrats and Republicans is both maddening and beside the point. Until campaign finance reform laws are passed, both parties will continue to raise money from every legal source with truly reckless abandon.</p>
        <p>But that does not change the fact that the Gore-Lieberman ticket has pledged to make reform its top priority, while the Bush-Cheney ticket opposes it. That is what counts.</p>
        <p>M. J. ROSENBERG  Chevy Chase, Md., Aug. 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
